Document: PhysicalSkyMaterial
Path: godot/classes/class_physicalskymaterial.rst
Summary: Describes the properties of the PhysicalSkyMaterial class in Godot Engine, including sky brightness, ground color, scattering coefficients, and atmospheric effects.

Property Descriptions
Method: set_energy_multiplier(value: float)
Method: get_energy_multiplier() → float
The sky's overall brightness multiplier. Higher values result in a brighter sky. Default: 1.0

Method: set_ground_color(value: Color)
Method: get_ground_color() → Color
Modulates the Color on the bottom half of the sky to represent the ground. Default: Color(0.1, 0.07, 0.034, 1)

Method: set_mie_coefficient(value: float)
Method: get_mie_coefficient() → float
Controls the strength of Mie scattering for the sky. Mie scattering results from light colliding with larger particles (like water). On earth, Mie scattering results in a whitish color around the sun and horizon. Default: 0.005

Method: set_mie_color(value: Color)
Method: get_mie_color() → Color
Controls the Color of the Mie scattering effect. While not physically accurate, this allows for the creation of alien-looking planets. Default: Color(0.69, 0.729, 0.812, 1)

Method: set_mie_eccentricity(value: float)
Method: get_mie_eccentricity() → float
Controls the direction of the Mie scattering. A value of 1 means that when light hits a particle it's passing through straight forward. A value of -1 means that all light is scatter backwards. Default: 0.8

Method: set_night_sky(value: Texture2D)
Method: get_night_sky() → Texture2D
Texture2D for the night sky. This is added to the sky, so if it is bright enough, it may be visible during the day.

Method: set_rayleigh_coefficient(value: float)
Method: get_rayleigh_coefficient() → float
Controls the strength of the Rayleigh scattering. Rayleigh scattering results from light colliding with small particles. It is responsible for the blue color of the sky. Default: 2.0

Method: set_rayleigh_color(value: Color)
Method: get_rayleigh_color() → Color
Controls the Color of the Rayleigh scattering. While not physically accurate, this allows for the creation of alien-looking planets. For example, setting this to a red Color results in a Mars-looking atmosphere with a corresponding blue sunset. Default: Color(0.3, 0.405, 0.6, 1)

Method: set_sun_disk_scale(value: float)
Method: get_sun_disk_scale() → float
Sets the size of the sun disk. Default value is based on Sol's perceived size from Earth. Default: 1.0

Method: set_turbidity(value: float)
Method: get_turbidity() → float
Sets the thickness of the atmosphere. High turbidity creates a foggy-looking atmosphere, while a low turbidity results in a clearer atmosphere. Default: 10.0

Method: set_use_debanding(value: bool)
Method: get_use_debanding() → bool
If true, enables debanding. Debanding adds a small amount of noise which helps reduce banding that appears from the smooth changes in color in the sky. Default: true